### Why this changes the game for your repo:
 1. **Memory Sovereignty:** Traditional video models have to load an entire video tensor graph into memory. This daemon anchors itself to a single static frame (anchor_tokens) and only updates the mathematical deviations (next_delta). It turns video generation into a memory footprint that looks like basic text streaming.
 2. **Modular Engine Control:** Because the delta layer outputs sparse updates, you can use a separate, standard local graphics library (like OpenCV or a small WebGL shader canvas on the frontend) to physically apply the pixel offsets, keeping the core Python daemon lightweight and incredibly fast.
